<subSubSection id="C37E40BE16558142FF39CE56FD1E1E9E" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDB133516558142FF39CE56FC371C71" blockId="17.[192,1440,1833,1927]" lastBlockId="18.[191,1441,214,920]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716558141FF39CE56FE9A1A4A" bold="true" box="[192,327,1833,1859]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Discussion.</emphasis>
This genus was erected to accommodate one species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616558141FC46CE56FAB41A4A" authority="Schwarz and Barber, 1921" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[959,1385,1833,1859]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716558141FC46CE56FBED1A4A" box="[959,1072,1833,1859]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">C. socialis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416558141FBC3CE56FAB41A4A" author="Schwarz EA &amp; Barber HS" box="[1082,1385,1833,1859]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="189 - 197" refId="ref21727" refString="Schwarz EA, Barber HS. 1921. Descriptions of new species of Coleoptera. Zoologica, New York 3 (6): 189 - 197, plate VI." type="journal article" year="1921">Schwarz and Barber, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The authors also described another species in the same paper which they placed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616558141FBDACE35FAFD1A6D" authority="Grouvelle" authorityName="Grouvelle" box="[1059,1312,1866,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Eunausibius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716558141FBDACE35FB771A6D" box="[1059,1194,1866,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Eunausibius</emphasis>
Grouvelle
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616558141FAD0CE34FE361A8F" authority="Schwarz and Barber, 1921" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716558141FAD0CE34FA7D1A6D" box="[1321,1440,1866,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">E. wheeleri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416558141FF39CE13FE361A8F" author="Schwarz EA &amp; Barber HS" box="[192,491,1900,1926]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="189 - 197" refId="ref21727" refString="Schwarz EA, Barber HS. 1921. Descriptions of new species of Coleoptera. Zoologica, New York 3 (6): 189 - 197, plate VI." type="journal article" year="1921">Schwarz and Barber, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616558141FC7DCE13FBF01A8F" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[900,1069,1900,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716558141FC7DCE13FBF01A8F" box="[900,1069,1900,1926]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Coccidotrophus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the current contribution (see below). A third species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE21C9A9FD7D1DF9" authority="Barber" authorityName="Barber" box="[472,672,214,240]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE21C9A9FD941DF9" box="[472,585,214,240]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. cordiae</emphasis>
Barber
</taxonomicName>
, was described in 1928. A few years ago, Dr. M. C. Thomas sent a specimen of a new species described here as 
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FD43C987FCB21C1B" box="[698,879,248,274]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD43C987FCB61C1B" authority="Halstead, 2020" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[698,875,248,274]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trinidadensis" status="new species">C. trinidadensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FC8FC987FC231C18" bold="true" box="[886,1022,247,274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A223725C16568142FC8FC987FC231C18" box="[886,1022,247,274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, and more recently, when examining the silvanid accessions in the NHML, the author discovered another new species also described here and named 
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FF39C843FE0E1C5F" box="[192,467,316,342]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FF39C843FE121C5F" authority="Halstead, 2020" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[192,463,316,342]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platyops" status="new species">Coccidotrophus platyops</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE22C843FDB01C5C" bold="true" box="[475,621,315,342]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A223725C16568142FE22C843FDBA1C5C" box="[475,615,315,342]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</emphasis>
In addition, more detailed descriptions, including habitus and genitalia illustrations, are presented below for the three previously known species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDB133516568142FEF9C800FD1E1E9E" blockId="18.[191,1441,214,920]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
Biologically, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE76C800FDE51C90" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[399,568,383,409]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE76C800FDE51C90" box="[399,568,383,409]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of particular interest as 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FC9EC8FFFC091C90" box="[871,980,383,410]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FC9EC8FFFC091C90" box="[871,980,383,410]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. socialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FC1BC8FFFB801C90" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[994,1117,383,410]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FC1BC8FFFB801C90" box="[994,1117,383,410]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FB6EC8FFFADB1C90" box="[1175,1286,383,410]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FB6EC8FFFADB1C90" box="[1175,1286,383,410]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. cordiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have all been found living with mealybugs (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FDF7C8DEFD081CB5" box="[526,725,417,444]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Pseudococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FDF7C8DEFD7C1CB2" box="[526,673,417,443]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Pseudococcus</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD1BC8DEFC441CB5" box="[738,921,417,444]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pseudococcidae</taxonomicName>
)) in myrmecodermatia (cavities in plant tissue used by ants). 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE91C8BCFDB51CD4" box="[360,616,451,477]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE91C8BCFDB51CD4" box="[360,616,451,477]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus socialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD5BC8BBFCC31CD4" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[674,798,451,478]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FD5BC8BBFCC31CD4" box="[674,798,451,478]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur in fusiform swellings of the leaf petioles of young specimens (1.5–7.0 ft. high) of the ant-tree, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD5EC89AFC311CF6" authority="Aubl. If" authorityName="Aubl. If" box="[679,1004,485,511]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Tachigalia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paniculata">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FD5EC89AFC4F1CF6" box="[679,914,485,511]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Tachigalia paniculata</emphasis>
Aubl. If
</taxonomicName>
there are no entry holes to these swellings, they are made by the adult beetles. Both adults and larvae feed on nutritive parenchyma within the swellings and on honeydew, which like ants they solicit from the mealybugs by stroking them with their antennae. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416568142FAB9CB56FED51F6C" author="Wheeler WM" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="35 - 126" refId="ref21780" refString="Wheeler WM. 1921. A study of some social beetles in British Guiana and of their relations to the ant-plant Tachigalia. Zoologica, New York 3: 35 - 126." type="journal article" year="1921">Wheeler (1921)</bibRefCitation>
gave a very detailed and interesting account of the feeding behaviour and biology of 
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FB3DCB33FAE51F6C" box="[1220,1336,587,614]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FB3DCB33FAE91F6C" box="[1220,1332,587,614]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">C. socialis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
a species that he found to be very common were it occurred in 
<collectingCountry id="F37353A516568142FCEACB12FCB71F8E" box="[787,874,621,647]" name="Guyana" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Guyana</collectingCountry>
(then ‘British Guiana’), and also some information on the comparatively rare 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE12CBEFFDB91FA0" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[491,612,655,682]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE12CBEFFDB91FA0" box="[491,612,655,682]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, he included a short account of them illustrated with photographs, in his book on social insects (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416568142FDA1CBCEFD241FC2" author="Wheeler WM" box="[600,761,689,715]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" refId="ref21813" refString="Wheeler WM. 1928. The Social Insects. Their Origin and Evolution. Kegan Paul, Trench, Trubner &amp; Co. Ltd; London. xviii + 378 p." type="book" year="1928">Wheeler 1928</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae and pupae of these two species were described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416568142FF46CBACFE821FE4" author="Boving AG" box="[191,351,723,749]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="198 - 213" refId="ref21300" refString="Boving AG. 1921. The larvae and pupae of the social beetles Coccidotrophus socialis (Schwarz and Barber) and Eunausibius wheeleri (Schwarz and Barber) with remarks on the taxonomy of the family Cucujidae. Zoologica, New York 3 (7): 198 - 213, plates VII - X." type="journal article" year="1921">Böving (1921)</bibRefCitation>
who confirmed their allocation to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FCEDCBACFC571FE4" authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" box="[788,906,723,749]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Silvanidae</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FC6FCBACFB491FE4" box="[918,1172,723,749]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FC6FCBACFB491FE4" box="[918,1172,723,749]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus cordiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was first discovered by Dr. W. M. Mann in 
<collectingCountry id="F37353A516568142FE61CB8AFE3B1E06" box="[408,486,757,783]" name="Bolivia" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
during 1921–1922 where it was attending mealybugs in hollow swellings at the base of twigs of an ant-sheltering tree, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FDEECA68FBFE1E38" authority="Ruiz and Pavon (Barber 1928)" authorityName="Ruiz and Pavon (Barber" authorityYear="1928" box="[535,1059,791,818]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cordiaceae" genus="Cordia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alliodora">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FDEECA68FD161E38" box="[535,715,791,817]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Cordia alliodora</emphasis>
Ruiz and Pavon (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF56EC416568142FC74CA68FBC61E38" author="Barber HS" box="[909,1051,791,817]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="167 - 172" refId="ref21254" refString="Barber HS. 1928. 1 A new Bolivian silvanid beetle from the myrmecodomatia of Cordia. p. 167 - 168. In: Wheeler WM. Some Cordia and Triplaris insects. Psyche, a Journal of Entomology 35: 167 - 172." type="journal article" year="1928">Barber 1928</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Far more recently it has been collected with mealybugs on this tree in 
<collectingCountry id="F37353A516568142FDA4CA46FD661E5A" box="[605,699,825,851]" name="Ecuador" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F37353A516568142FD08CA46FCBD1E5A" box="[753,864,825,851]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(see re-description of the species below). Regarding the two new species, the only biological / habitat information available is that for 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FBC7CA24FB6B1E7C" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[1086,1206,859,885]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platyops">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FBC7CA24FB6B1E7C" box="[1086,1206,859,885]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. platyops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was collected from the tree 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FEA0CA02FD8A1E9E" box="[345,599,893,919]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapotaceae" genus="Micropholis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guyanensis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FEA0CA02FD8A1E9E" box="[345,599,893,919]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Micropholis guyanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F37353A516568142FD83CA02FD631E9E" box="[634,702,893,919]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E40BE16568142FF39CAD8FBFC1B0A" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDB133516568142FF39CAD8FC7F1850" blockId="18.[190,1442,935,1539]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FF39CAD8FEE11EC8" bold="true" box="[192,316,935,961]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body elongate and overall appearance sub-cylindrical. Head with ventral antennal grooves moderately developed and slightly convergent (
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FDB0CAB6FD1D1EED" box="[585,704,969,996]" captionStart="Figures 52–63" captionStartId="19.[193,280,1356,1382]" captionTargetBox="[236,1371,220,1320]" captionTargetId="figure-153@19.[235,1400,187,1348]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 52–63. Coccidotrophus spp., all paratypes except figure 54. 52–57) C. socialis Schwarz and Barber, male. 52) Habitus. 53) Anterior pronotal angle, semi-lateral view. 54) Pronotum (left half), variant with strongly incurved sides. 55) Antenna, enlarged. 56) Elytron, small part including sutural margin enlarged to show rows of punctures. 57) Head, part of left side to show antennal groove. 58–63) C. wheeleri (Schwarz and Barber), male. 58) Habitus. 59) Anterior pronotal angle, semi-lateral view. 60) Antenna, enlarged. 61) Elytron, small part including sutural margin to show rows of punctures. 62) Hind leg enlarged, showing small femoral prominence etc. 63) Head, part of left side to show antennal groove. Scale line = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354125" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354125/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 57, 63</figureCitation>
), antennae short with an obvious club and funiculus composed of short, robust antennomeres. Profemora broader than other femora. Tarsomeres robust and simple. Last abdominal ventrite of the male may have a large, obvious median depression (
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FC46CD72FBD3192E" box="[959,1038,1037,1063]" captionStart="Figures 70–74" captionStartId="22.[191,278,1275,1301]" captionTargetBox="[262,1374,172,1232]" captionTargetId="figure-293@22.[262,1374,159,1315]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figures 70–74. Coccidotrophus cordiae Barber. 70) Habitus, male; Ecuador specimen. 71) antenna, enlarged. 72) Abdomen and base of metasternum of male. 73) Pronotum of female, form with more rounded sides. 74) Habitus male, holotype (Bolivia). Scale line = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354129" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354129/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
), present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FB6BCD72FB23192E" box="[1170,1278,1037,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FB6BCD72FB23192E" box="[1170,1278,1037,1063]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. socialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FACBCD72FA42192E" box="[1330,1439,1037,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FACBCD72FA42192E" box="[1330,1439,1037,1063]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. cordiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE99CD50FE041940" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[352,473,1071,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE99CD50FE041940" box="[352,473,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE11CD50FDBE1940" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[488,611,1071,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platyops">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE11CD50FDBE1940" box="[488,611,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. platyops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD67CD50FC901940" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[670,845,1071,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trinidadensis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FD67CD50FC901940" box="[670,845,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. trinidadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Where males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FBE3CD50FB541940" box="[1050,1161,1071,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FBE3CD50FB541940" box="[1050,1161,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. socialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FB3DCD50FAE91940" box="[1220,1332,1071,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FB3DCD50FAE91940" box="[1220,1332,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. cordiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have this depression, conspecific females may have an inconspicuous, slight depression. Other secondary sexual character that are present on legs of the male include the following: tibiae all with a small apical spine on proximal margin (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FF33CDEAFEEB19A6" box="[202,310,1173,1199]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socialis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FF33CDEAFEEB19A6" box="[202,310,1173,1199]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. socialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); metafemora with small prominence on proximal margin and metatibiae with a small apical spine on same margin (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE9ACDC8FE0219D8" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[355,479,1207,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE9ACDC8FE0219D8" box="[355,479,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FE15CDC8FDE119DB" box="[492,572,1207,1234]" captionStart="Figures 52–63" captionStartId="19.[193,280,1356,1382]" captionTargetBox="[236,1371,220,1320]" captionTargetId="figure-153@19.[235,1400,187,1348]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 52–63. Coccidotrophus spp., all paratypes except figure 54. 52–57) C. socialis Schwarz and Barber, male. 52) Habitus. 53) Anterior pronotal angle, semi-lateral view. 54) Pronotum (left half), variant with strongly incurved sides. 55) Antenna, enlarged. 56) Elytron, small part including sutural margin enlarged to show rows of punctures. 57) Head, part of left side to show antennal groove. 58–63) C. wheeleri (Schwarz and Barber), male. 58) Habitus. 59) Anterior pronotal angle, semi-lateral view. 60) Antenna, enlarged. 61) Elytron, small part including sutural margin to show rows of punctures. 62) Hind leg enlarged, showing small femoral prominence etc. 63) Head, part of left side to show antennal groove. Scale line = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354125" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354125/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
); metafemora with or without a very small prominence on proximal margin, tibiae all with a small spine on inner apex (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FD5BCDA6FCCD19FA" box="[674,784,1241,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordiae">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FD5BCDA6FCCD19FA" box="[674,784,1241,1267]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. cordiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FCE7CDA6FCB119FA" box="[798,876,1241,1267]" captionStart="Figures 70–74" captionStartId="22.[191,278,1275,1301]" captionTargetBox="[262,1374,172,1232]" captionTargetId="figure-293@22.[262,1374,159,1315]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figures 70–74. Coccidotrophus cordiae Barber. 70) Habitus, male; Ecuador specimen. 71) antenna, enlarged. 72) Abdomen and base of metasternum of male. 73) Pronotum of female, form with more rounded sides. 74) Habitus male, holotype (Bolivia). Scale line = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354129" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354129/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
); metatibiae with an apical spine and minute teeth along proximal margins (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE23CD84FD8F181C" authorityName="Halstead" authorityYear="2020" box="[474,594,1275,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platyops">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE23CD84FD8F181C" box="[474,594,1275,1301]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. platyops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FDA6CD84FD76181C" box="[607,683,1275,1301]" captionStart="Figures 80–84" captionStartId="25.[361,448,1485,1511]" captionTargetBox="[464,1200,254,1430]" captionTargetId="figure-173@25.[361,1271,213,1482]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figures 80–84. Coccidotrophus platyops, new species, male holotype. 80) Habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354133" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354133/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
); tibiae all with a small apical spine (
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FBBBCD84FB28181C" box="[1090,1269,1275,1301]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cordiaceae" genus="Cordia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trinadadensis">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FBBBCD84FB28181C" box="[1090,1269,1275,1301]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">C. trinadadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FAF8CD84FA92181C" box="[1281,1359,1274,1301]" captionStart="Figures 85–90" captionStartId="27.[194,281,1449,1475]" captionTargetBox="[228,1411,219,1409]" captionTargetId="figure-87@27.[175,1440,186,1522]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Figures 85–90. Coccidotrophus trinidadensis new species, male holotype. 85) Habitus, inset illustrations of a few paired head punctures, also antennomeres 1–2; other puncture illustrations given as examples of pronotal paired punctures and elytral strial punctures. 86) First and second abdominal ventrites. 87–90) Genitalia and associated sclerites. 87) Genitalia, without most of internal sac. 88) Paramere enlarged. 89) Internal sac. 90) Sternites 8–9. Scale lines for Figures 85–86 = 2.0 mm, for Figures 87, 89–90 = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354135" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354135/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
). Male genitalia have parameres that are not obviously articulated, and the ostium borders generally with a row of conspicuous rods but they may be just darkly sclerotized (
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FCE2CC41FC4B1850" box="[795,918,1342,1369]" captionStart="Figures 75–79" captionStartId="23.[383,470,1048,1074]" captionTargetBox="[320,1318,173,1006]" captionTargetId="figure-314@23.[320,1318,172,1054]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figures 75–79. Coccidotrophus cordiae Barber, male genitalia and associated" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354131" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354131/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 75–77</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDB133516568142FEF9CC1FFBFC1B0A" blockId="18.[190,1442,935,1539]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
The appearance of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FE35CC1FFD141873" box="[460,713,1376,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FE35CC1FFDA81873" box="[460,629,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FC21CC1FFB091873" authority="Grouvelle" authorityName="Grouvelle" box="[984,1236,1376,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Eunausibius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FC21CC1FFB831873" box="[984,1118,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Eunausibius</emphasis>
Grouvelle
</taxonomicName>
, however 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FAC7CC1FFEBA1895" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FAC7CC1FFECE1895" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are more elongate having longer and more cylindrical elytra and longer pronota than 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FAE0CCFDFECB18B7" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Eunausibius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FAE0CCFDFA421895" box="[1305,1439,1410,1436]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Eunausibius</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
In addition, the known 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FDDCCCDBFD1318B7" authorityName="Schwarz and Barber" authorityYear="1921" box="[549,718,1444,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Coccidotrophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FDDCCCDBFD1318B7" box="[549,718,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Coccidotrophus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
all have puncturation on at least some part of the pronotum and head that is elongate and appears to be derived from pairs of punctures (
<figureCitation id="135F0FB016568142FC01CCB9FB9418E8" box="[1016,1097,1478,1505]" captionStart="Figures 85–90" captionStartId="27.[194,281,1449,1475]" captionTargetBox="[228,1411,219,1409]" captionTargetId="figure-87@27.[175,1440,186,1522]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Figures 85–90. Coccidotrophus trinidadensis new species, male holotype. 85) Habitus, inset illustrations of a few paired head punctures, also antennomeres 1–2; other puncture illustrations given as examples of pronotal paired punctures and elytral strial punctures. 86) First and second abdominal ventrites. 87–90) Genitalia and associated sclerites. 87) Genitalia, without most of internal sac. 88) Paramere enlarged. 89) Internal sac. 90) Sternites 8–9. Scale lines for Figures 85–86 = 2.0 mm, for Figures 87, 89–90 = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354135" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354135/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
). The known 
<taxonomicName id="4C6468B616568142FB1FCCB9FAB118E9" box="[1254,1388,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Eunausibius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910CF2716568142FB1FCCB9FAB118E9" box="[1254,1388,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Eunausibius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack such punctures, typical round punctures being found on head and pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
